{
  "title": "Monier-Williams Dictionary Quiz",
  "description": "Quiz dataset for learning to read and navigate the Monier-Williams Sanskrit-English Dictionary (MW). Concept questions, multiple-choice, headword-lookup, and trace-to-dhatu exercises drawn from Lessons 12-14 of Charles Wikner's 'A Practical Sanskrit Introductory'.",
  "source": {
    "work": "A Practical Sanskrit Introductory",
    "author": "Charles Wikner",
    "year": 1996,
    "license": "freely distributable",
    "file": "src/wikner.pdf",
    "lessons": [
      12,
      13,
      14
    ]
  },
  "caveats": [
    "Each lookup answer carries a CDSL entry id (the digital record's lnum, shown as [ID=…] in the entry) and a live listview URL, fetched from the Cologne getword_xml API; the digital page,column is preserved from the print via <pc> and is shown as e.g. '135a'.",
    "Transliteration is IAST; the API is queried in SLP1 (the cdsl.slp1 key). Entry ids are line-derived and can shift if MW is regenerated, so the headword/slp1 key is the more stable reference (cf. developers/api 'Clean-URL permalinks')."
  ],
  "answerKeyKeycols": "Page-column codes: a = first column, b = second column, c = third column.",
  "questions": [
    {
      "id": "L12-C01",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.3",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "question": "On what two organizing principles is the Monier-Williams dictionary built?",
      "answer": "Etymological (cognate words are gathered under the dhatu they share) AND alphabetical.",
      "tags": [
        "structure"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C02",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.3",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "question": "How many distinct levels of alphabetical ordering does MW use?",
      "answer": "Four.",
      "tags": [
        "structure",
        "alphabetical-order"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C03",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.3",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "What is the FIRST (outermost) level of alphabetical order in MW?",
      "answer": "The main entry words printed in Devanagari script, alphabetized in Sanskrit order.",
      "tags": [
        "alphabetical-order"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C04",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.3",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "What is the SECOND level of alphabetical order?",
      "answer": "Derived words listed under each Devanagari entry, printed in transliterated Roman and alphabetized independently of the outer Devanagari sequence.",
      "tags": [
        "alphabetical-order"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C05",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.3",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "What is the THIRD level of alphabetical order?",
      "answer": "Samasa (compounds) beginning with a hyphen, listed alphabetically within an entry's paragraph; mentally replace the leading hyphen with the entry word.",
      "tags": [
        "alphabetical-order",
        "compounds"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C06",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.3",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "question": "What is the FOURTH (innermost) level of alphabetical order?",
      "answer": "Sub-sub-entries listed in alphabetical order under a third-level hyphenated sub-entry (e.g. -parisodhaka and -varalocana under -kshetra under Buddhi).",
      "tags": [
        "alphabetical-order",
        "compounds"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C07",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.3",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "What are the two main advantages of MW's etymological arrangement?",
      "answer": "(1) Cognate words from one dhatu are gathered together, giving breadth of understanding; (2) it is trivial to trace a word back to its dhatu, giving depth/insight.",
      "tags": [
        "structure"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C08",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.3",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "question": "Under the entry 'Buddha', a bold sub-entry printed as '-kalpa' represents:",
      "options": [
        "A cross-reference to another dictionary",
        "An alternate spelling of Buddha",
        "A grammatical note about the entry",
        "A samasa formed by appending it to the entry word, i.e. Buddhakalpa"
      ],
      "answer": "A samasa formed by appending it to the entry word, i.e. Buddhakalpa",
      "tags": [
        "compounds"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C09",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.4",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "question": "What do the page-heading (running-head) words at the top of each MW page indicate?",
      "answer": "The first and last entry words found on that page, given in both Devanagari and Roman transliteration.",
      "tags": [
        "navigation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C10",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.4",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "question": "Why can the page-heading words mislead you?",
      "answer": "They do not indicate which of the four alphabetical levels each word belongs to; the two may sit at different levels, or even appear in reverse alphabetical order because they derive from different Devanagari entries.",
      "tags": [
        "navigation",
        "pitfalls"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L12-C11",
      "lesson": 12,
      "section": "12.3",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "As you scan the derived words of a dhatu like budh, the first vowel strengthens Bu- to Bo- to Bau-. What are these two strengthened grades called?",
      "answer": "guna and vrddhi.",
      "tags": [
        "grammar"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L13-C01",
      "lesson": 13,
      "section": "13.5",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "What does the small raised circle ('the little circle') mean in MW?",
      "answer": "It is the standard Devanagari abbreviation symbol marking the first or last part of a word to be supplied from context; MW also uses it to abbreviate English words to save space (e.g. con° = conscious, °ly = consciously, °ness = consciousness).",
      "tags": [
        "symbols",
        "abbreviations"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L13-C02",
      "lesson": 13,
      "section": "13.5",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "question": "What do the four caret/breve accent marks placed over transliterated vowels indicate?",
      "answer": "The length of the two vowels that merged at a compound's junction — short+short, short+long, long+short, or long+long — so that each component word can be split apart and looked up separately.",
      "tags": [
        "symbols",
        "sandhi",
        "compounds"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L13-C03",
      "lesson": 13,
      "section": "13.6",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "Besides showing that a word is appended to the entry word, what else does a leading hyphen on a sub-entry tell you?",
      "answer": "That the hyphenated element is itself a word you can look up separately in the dictionary.",
      "tags": [
        "symbols",
        "compounds"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L13-C04",
      "lesson": 13,
      "section": "13.4",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "question": "Where in MW is the List of Works and Authors (the key to source abbreviations such as Bhag. and MBh.)?",
      "answer": "Page xxxiii of the Introduction.",
      "tags": [
        "references",
        "abbreviations"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L13-C05",
      "lesson": 13,
      "section": "13.4",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "question": "In MW, the abbreviation 'MBh.' stands for which text?",
      "options": [
        "Bhagavad-gita",
        "Manu-bhashya",
        "Mahabharata",
        "Mundaka"
      ],
      "answer": "Mahabharata",
      "explanation": "Bhag. abbreviates Bhagavad-gita; MBh. abbreviates Mahabharata.",
      "tags": [
        "references",
        "abbreviations"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L13-C06",
      "lesson": 13,
      "section": "13.7",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "question": "If a word is not in the main body of MW, where should you look next?",
      "answer": "The Supplement — 'Additions and Corrections' — beginning on page 1308.",
      "tags": [
        "navigation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L13-C07",
      "lesson": 13,
      "section": "13.2",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "question": "MW uniquely distinguishes two kinds of anusvara. What are they, and what should the student do about it?",
      "answer": "A 'true' anusvara (n-dot, inherent in the word from its dhatu, e.g. amsa, himsa) versus a 'substitute' anusvara (m-dot, produced by the rules of grammar, e.g. sam + sara = samsara). This distinction is peculiar to MW; the student may treat the two as synonymous — both simply the anusvara.",
      "tags": [
        "encoding",
        "pitfalls"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L14-C01",
      "lesson": 14,
      "section": "14.1",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "Because MW is etymologically arranged, how do you trace a transliterated (Roman) entry back to its dhatu?",
      "answer": "Follow the entry words backwards (toward the start of the alphabet) until you reach a Devanagari entry — the outermost level — then look up the component verb/prefix and continue back to the root.",
      "tags": [
        "etymology",
        "navigation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L14-C02",
      "lesson": 14,
      "section": "14.5",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "You cannot find a short word of one or two syllables in MW. What is the likely reason and the recourse?",
      "answer": "It may not be listed at all (e.g. the irregular declensions of pronouns); the only recourse is to lists of paradigms.",
      "tags": [
        "pitfalls"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L14-C03",
      "lesson": 14,
      "section": "14.5",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "question": "What is the strategy for finding a difficult word of three or more syllables?",
      "answer": "Treat it as a samasa and use the sandhi rules to split it into parts at every syllable, looking up each candidate split until one is found.",
      "tags": [
        "sandhi",
        "compounds"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L14-C04",
      "lesson": 14,
      "section": "14.4",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "question": "Why is 'Astanga' hard to find on the page its heading words suggest?",
      "options": [
        "MW gives a separate entry word for a samasa whose adjoining word begins with 'a', so it sits on the next page (117)",
        "It is only in the Supplement",
        "It is spelled differently in the dictionary",
        "The heading words are printed in reverse order"
      ],
      "answer": "MW gives a separate entry word for a samasa whose adjoining word begins with 'a', so it sits on the next page (117)",
      "tags": [
        "pitfalls",
        "navigation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "L14-C05",
      "lesson": 14,
      "section": "14.4",
      "type": "concept",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "question": "Looking up 'Vicara' or 'Sattva', the heading words do not lead you straight to the word. What general technique resolves this?",
      "answer": "Escape out of the current alphabetical level up to the next higher level (ultimately the outermost Devanagari entry) and search from there, following any cross-references.",
      "tags": [
        "navigation",
        "pitfalls"
      ]
    },
